                    <msContents>
                        <summary> Illustrated copy of Abū al-Majd Majdūd ibn Ādam Sanāʼī
                            al-Ghaznavī's <title>Ḥadīqat al-ḥaqīqah</title> (The Walled Garden of Truth), a mystical Sufi epic.</summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_12-item1">
                            <author key="person_96993055" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/96993055/">
                                <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Sanāʼī
                                    al-Ghaznavī, Abū al-Majd Majdūd ibn Ādam, d. ca. 1150</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="fa">سنايى غزنوى، ابو المجد مجدود ابن
                                    آدم</persName>
                            </author>
                            <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_285">Ḥadīqat al-ḥaqīqah</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_285">حديقة الحقيقة</title>
                             <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="chart">
                                <extent> 318 folios <dimensions type="leaf" unit="cm">
                                        <height>23.8</height>
                                        <width>13.3</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="cm">
                                        <height>16.5</height>
                                        <width>7</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="2" ruledLines="16" n="mistara"/>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"/>
                        </handDesc>
                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="illustration">7 miniatures, three of which are
                                double-page compositions, in the Shiraz style at the beginning of
                                the seventeenth century. </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="decoration">There are illuminated headings on folios
                                    <locus from="2b" to="2b">2b</locus> (preface) and <locus
                                    from="10b" to="10b">10b</locus> (beginning of text). The text of
                                these folios and the facing pages are also decorated. The central
                                column ruling of each page is not formed of the usual pair of fine
                                gold lines outlined in black and instead features a pair of fine
                                gold lines flanked by pale green lines.</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <decoNote>Fairly modern oriental binding of dark red leather, inlaid
                                with gilt medallions and pendants. The spine is inscribed with
                                HUDDEEKA HUKEEM SUNNAIE. The original doublures, of fairly rough
                                gilt cut-out work on various coloured backgrounds, have been
                                incorporated, but are somewhat damaged.</decoNote>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1607">Dated the End of Rajab
                                the revered, the year 1016 (1607 CE).</origDate>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>There are colophons on folios <locus from="10a" to="10a">10a</locus>
                                and <locus from="317a" to="317a">317a</locus>. The former gives the
                                scribes name, Muhammad al-Qiwami. The latter gives the date.</p>
                            <p>Formerly part of the collection of the first European editor of the
                                <title>Shahnama</title> of Firdawsi (Calcutta, 1829),<persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/316003640" key="person_316003640"
                                    >Turner Macan (1792-1836)</persName>. The manuscript then became
                                part of the collection of the Persian scholar <persName
                                    type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/#Bland,_Nathaniel,_1803-1865"
                                    key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>.
                                Bland’s oriental manuscripts were sold through Bernard Quaritch in
                                1866 to <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/#Crawford,_Alexander_Crawford_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1812-1880"
                                    key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of
                                    Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands, on behalf of the John Rylands
                                Library, in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/#Crawford,_James_Ludovic_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1847-1913"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
